WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:18.160
The Adventures in the Grasslands by Yulia Puchkova

00:18.160 --> 00:23.520
Chapter 1 Here I am.

00:23.520 --> 00:25.520
Here I am.

00:25.520 --> 00:27.520
Here I am.

00:27.520 --> 00:33.520
Thinks Spotty, a small, handsome, baby giraffe.

00:33.520 --> 00:37.520
Mother is looking at him and listening to him.

00:37.520 --> 00:41.520
Of course, he can't talk.

00:41.520 --> 00:46.520
But she understands his every word.

00:46.520 --> 00:49.520
Who are you, Spotty asks?

00:49.520 --> 00:52.520
I'm your mom, she answers.

00:52.520 --> 00:55.520
My mum, he asks.

00:55.520 --> 00:57.520
Who is mum?

00:57.520 --> 01:00.520
Mum is your good friend.

01:00.520 --> 01:03.520
Mum is always with you.

01:03.520 --> 01:07.520
And you are Spotty, my son.

01:07.520 --> 01:09.520
Oh, great!

01:09.520 --> 01:14.520
Spotty says and smiles to mother.

01:14.520 --> 01:16.520
How are you?

01:16.520 --> 01:18.520
Mother asks.

01:18.520 --> 01:20.520
I'm hungry.

01:20.520 --> 01:22.520
Spotty answers.

01:22.520 --> 01:24.520
Don't worry.

01:24.520 --> 01:29.520
I'm not only your friend, I'm your dining room too.

01:29.520 --> 01:33.520
I've got a lot of nice milk for you.

01:33.520 --> 01:38.520
Stand under me and drink, she says.

01:38.520 --> 01:42.520
Spotty, drinks and drinks.

01:42.520 --> 01:47.520
The milk is warm and tasty, and it never ends.

01:47.520 --> 01:53.520
Now, he isn't hungry anymore.

01:53.520 --> 02:01.520
Mother opens her mouth, and Spotty can see a long, thick thing inside.

02:01.520 --> 02:03.520
What's that?

02:03.520 --> 02:04.520
He asks.

02:04.520 --> 02:06.520
It's my tongue.

02:06.520 --> 02:08.520
Mother answers.

02:08.520 --> 02:12.520
Why is it so long?

02:12.520 --> 02:15.520
Because we are giraffes.

02:15.520 --> 02:21.520
I think only giraffes have got very long tongues, mother says.

02:21.520 --> 02:28.520
Are there many giraffes, or are there only you and me, Spotty asks?

02:28.520 --> 02:30.520
Mother smiles.

02:30.520 --> 02:35.520
Of course, there are a lot of giraffes.

02:35.520 --> 02:38.520
Soon, we can visit them.

02:38.520 --> 02:43.520
But now, I must teach you to walk and run.

02:43.520 --> 02:48.520
Spotty gets up and starts walking.

02:48.520 --> 02:52.520
What a clever baby I have got, mother laughs.

02:52.520 --> 02:55.520
Now, try to run.

02:55.520 --> 02:58.520
Spotty tries, but falls down.

02:58.520 --> 03:01.520
I've got too many legs, he says.

03:01.520 --> 03:03.520
They can't run altogether.

03:03.520 --> 03:07.520
Then tell them to run in turn, says mother.

03:07.520 --> 03:12.520
First, your left legs run, then your right ones.

03:12.520 --> 03:16.520
And which of them are left, Spotty asks.

03:16.520 --> 03:22.520
Can you hear a strange beat inside your body?

03:22.520 --> 03:24.520
Spotty listens.

03:24.520 --> 03:26.520
Yes.

03:26.520 --> 03:28.520
It's here.

03:28.520 --> 03:31.520
This is your heart.

03:31.520 --> 03:33.520
It's on the left.

03:33.520 --> 03:40.520
Your left legs are on the left too, says mother.

03:40.520 --> 03:46.520
Why have I got four legs and only one heart, Spotty asks?

03:46.520 --> 03:49.520
And why is it on the left?

03:49.520 --> 03:52.520
Nobody knows.

03:52.520 --> 03:55.520
But I think you can't run with one leg.

03:55.520 --> 03:58.520
And four hearts must be too noisy.

03:58.520 --> 04:03.520
Spotty looks in his mum's eyes.

04:03.520 --> 04:06.520
They are big and clever.

04:06.520 --> 04:10.520
And they are very kind.

04:10.520 --> 04:14.520
Let's play, son, she says.

04:14.520 --> 04:19.520
They start walking to a tall tree.

04:19.520 --> 04:25.520
Spotty can't walk fast, but mother is walking behind him.

04:25.520 --> 04:30.520
When they come to the tree, Spotty cries.

04:30.520 --> 04:33.520
I'm the first.

04:33.520 --> 04:36.520
He is happy.

04:47.520 --> 04:49.520
Chapter Two.

04:49.520 --> 04:51.520
My family.

04:51.520 --> 04:54.520
Hi. My name is Jack.

04:54.520 --> 04:58.520
I'm a boy, and I'm twelve.

04:58.520 --> 05:01.520
I live with my parents in Africa.

05:01.520 --> 05:04.520
My parents are scientists.

05:04.520 --> 05:07.520
They know a lot about African animals.

05:07.520 --> 05:10.520
I have got a sister.

05:10.520 --> 05:12.520
Her name is Jill.

05:12.520 --> 05:15.520
She is twenty-three.

05:15.520 --> 05:18.520
Jill doesn't live with us.

05:18.520 --> 05:22.520
She lives with her husband, Bill.

05:22.520 --> 05:25.520
I don't like Bill.

05:25.520 --> 05:29.520
If Jill wants something, Bill always does it.

05:29.520 --> 05:34.520
Sometimes these are very silly or bad things.

05:34.520 --> 05:39.520
One day, I'm visiting my sister and her husband.

05:39.520 --> 05:47.520
We're having coffee when suddenly she says, Bill, I want to have a pet giraffe.

05:47.520 --> 05:50.520
Bill's eyes get very big.

05:50.520 --> 05:53.520
He hasn't got a face now.

05:53.520 --> 05:55.520
Only eyes.

05:55.520 --> 05:57.520
Yes.

05:57.520 --> 06:01.520
A pet giraffe repeats my sister.

06:01.520 --> 06:03.520
It can live in the hall.

06:03.520 --> 06:05.520
Our hall is very big.

06:05.520 --> 06:09.520
Bill's eyes get normal, and he says,

06:09.520 --> 06:11.520
Okay, dear.

06:11.520 --> 06:15.520
I think I can get you a giraffe.

06:15.520 --> 06:18.520
Where do you want to get it?

06:19.520 --> 06:22.520
In the grasslands, of course, he answers.

06:22.520 --> 06:24.520
We can't buy a giraffe.

06:24.520 --> 06:27.520
We haven't got much money.

06:27.520 --> 06:30.520
You mustn't do that, I cry.

06:30.520 --> 06:34.520
You can have serious problems with the police.

06:34.520 --> 06:35.520
Why?

06:35.520 --> 06:40.520
I can find a stray cat or a stray dog in the street.

06:40.520 --> 06:44.520
Why can't I find a stray giraffe?

06:44.520 --> 06:46.520
I look at Bill.

06:46.520 --> 06:50.520
Sometimes he is very silly.

06:50.520 --> 06:55.520
And it is all because of my sister.

06:55.520 --> 07:01.520
Jack, don't tell our parents about it, Jill asks, please.

07:01.520 --> 07:04.520
And she smiles at me.

07:04.520 --> 07:09.520
I think you can't hide a giraffe in the house, I say.

07:09.520 --> 07:15.520
I stand up, say goodbye to them, and walk to the door.

07:15.520 --> 07:20.520
But, suddenly, I have an idea.

07:20.520 --> 07:25.520
Bill, can you take me with you?

07:25.520 --> 07:29.520
I can help you to catch the giraffe.

07:29.520 --> 07:31.520
Great, says Bill.

07:31.520 --> 07:40.520
Tomorrow, at six o'clock in the morning.

07:40.520 --> 07:43.520
This night, I can't sleep.

07:43.520 --> 07:49.520
I am thinking about my bad sister and silly Bill.

07:49.520 --> 07:53.520
I am thinking about that poor giraffe, too.

07:53.520 --> 07:57.520
Giraffes must live in the grasslands.

07:57.520 --> 08:02.520
They are tall, big and strong, and they must walk free.

08:02.520 --> 08:06.520
They must have a lot of trees around.

08:06.520 --> 08:09.520
They love eating fresh leaves.

08:09.520 --> 08:12.520
And if people want to look at them,

08:12.520 --> 08:16.520
they can watch a film or go on a safari.

08:16.520 --> 08:24.520
It is very wrong to catch giraffes and put them in cages or houses.

08:24.520 --> 08:27.520
Then I'm not thinking anymore.

08:27.520 --> 08:32.520
I am sleeping.

08:32.520 --> 08:42.520
Chapter 3.

08:42.520 --> 08:45.520
Preparations

08:45.520 --> 08:47.520
My alarm clock rings.

08:47.520 --> 08:49.520
I wake up.

08:49.520 --> 08:52.520
It is sunny and hot.

08:52.520 --> 08:55.520
I am happy.

08:55.520 --> 08:59.520
It is the first day of the summer holidays.

08:59.520 --> 09:01.520
I am free.

09:01.520 --> 09:05.520
I can swim or play football.

09:05.520 --> 09:11.520
Suddenly, I remember my sister and her silly husband.

09:11.520 --> 09:16.520
They want to have a pet giraffe.

09:16.520 --> 09:20.520
Today, Bill is going to the grasslands.

09:20.520 --> 09:24.520
He wants to catch a nice baby giraffe.

09:24.520 --> 09:27.520
And I am going with him.

09:27.520 --> 09:32.520
I hope he can't catch it.

09:32.520 --> 09:34.520
I look at the clock.

09:34.520 --> 09:36.520
It is six o'clock.

09:36.520 --> 09:39.520
My parents are at work.

09:39.520 --> 09:41.520
I get up.

09:41.520 --> 09:44.520
Put on my shorts and the t-shirt.

09:44.520 --> 09:47.520
They are bright red.

09:47.520 --> 09:49.520
I don't often wear red,

09:49.520 --> 09:54.520
but today this color can help me.

09:54.520 --> 09:59.520
Dad says giraffes can see some bright colors.

09:59.520 --> 10:03.520
I hope they can see the red color.

10:03.520 --> 10:09.520
I put on a red cap, open the door, and go out.

10:09.520 --> 10:12.520
I run to Bill and Jill's house.

10:12.520 --> 10:16.520
When I'm at their door, Bill comes out.

10:16.520 --> 10:21.520
He's wearing a brown shirt and brown shorts.

10:21.520 --> 10:28.520
He has got a green cap on his head and green gloves on his hands.

10:28.520 --> 10:33.520
He has got a big green bag on his back.

10:33.520 --> 10:40.520
He thinks he looks like a small tree with four green leaves.

10:40.520 --> 10:43.520
A nice tree, I say.

10:43.520 --> 10:45.520
Where?

10:45.520 --> 10:47.520
Bill asks.

10:47.520 --> 10:50.520
Opposite me, of course, I say.

10:50.520 --> 10:51.520
Aha!

10:51.520 --> 10:58.520
I'm very clever, Bill says, and smiles.

10:58.520 --> 11:02.520
Suddenly, Bill stops smiling.

11:02.520 --> 11:07.520
He's looking at my red costume.

11:07.520 --> 11:11.520
Why are you wearing red?

11:11.520 --> 11:13.520
He asks.

11:13.520 --> 11:16.520
You don't look like a tree.

11:16.520 --> 11:19.520
But I'm not a tree, I say.

11:19.520 --> 11:22.520
I'm the red light.

11:22.520 --> 11:28.520
What do you do when you see the red light in the street?

11:28.520 --> 11:31.520
I stop, Bill says.

11:31.520 --> 11:34.520
I stop too, I say.

11:34.520 --> 11:36.520
Everyone stops.

11:36.520 --> 11:45.520
Men and women, boys and girls, cats and dogs, and, of course, giraffes.

11:46.520 --> 11:52.520
You are great, Bill cries, and smiles at me again.

12:05.520 --> 12:07.520
Chapter 4.

12:07.520 --> 12:10.520
The hunt starts.

12:10.520 --> 12:12.520
We walk and walk.

12:12.520 --> 12:19.520
No, Bill is walking, and I am having fun.

12:19.520 --> 12:26.520
I look around and see a lot of funny insects and small animals.

12:26.520 --> 12:33.520
Sometimes I see snakes, but I'm not afraid of them.

12:33.520 --> 12:40.520
They get angry only if you hurt them or come too close.

12:40.520 --> 12:43.520
And I only look at them.

12:43.520 --> 12:47.520
Oh, there is a beautiful one.

12:47.520 --> 12:52.520
It is sleeping and shining in the sun.

12:52.520 --> 12:57.520
It looks like silver rings one around the other.

12:57.520 --> 13:03.520
When they sleep, they are so nice.

13:03.520 --> 13:06.520
What's the matter?

13:06.520 --> 13:09.520
Bill isn't walking anymore.

13:09.520 --> 13:14.520
He is standing and looking at some big animals far away.

13:14.520 --> 13:17.520
I look at them too.

13:17.520 --> 13:19.520
They are giraffes.

13:19.520 --> 13:22.520
They are great.

13:22.520 --> 13:26.520
Some giraffes are walking and shaking their long necks.

13:26.520 --> 13:31.520
The others are standing next to trees and eating leaves.

13:31.520 --> 13:34.520
Bill starts walking again.

13:34.520 --> 13:39.520
He opens his green bag and takes out a long thick rope.

13:39.520 --> 13:44.520
The rope has got a big loop at the end.

13:44.520 --> 13:47.520
My heart stops beating.

13:47.520 --> 13:52.520
I am so sorry for those beautiful animals.

13:52.520 --> 13:55.520
I must do something.

13:55.520 --> 14:02.520
But I am only twelve, and Bill is twenty-five.

14:02.520 --> 14:07.520
Suddenly, I can see a small baby giraffe.

14:07.520 --> 14:10.520
I think it is a boy.

14:10.520 --> 14:12.520
He is very young.

14:12.520 --> 14:15.520
He can't run fast.

14:15.520 --> 14:18.520
His mother is looking at him with love.

14:18.520 --> 14:21.520
She looks very happy and proud.

14:21.520 --> 14:23.520
I understand her.

14:23.520 --> 14:26.520
She has got a great baby.

14:26.520 --> 14:31.520
Her son is tall, and his skin has got dark brown spots.

14:31.520 --> 14:36.520
They look like squares with white lines around.

14:36.520 --> 14:41.520
My dad says there are many different kinds of giraffe.

14:41.520 --> 14:46.520
Here in East Africa, we have three kinds.

14:46.520 --> 14:49.520
This kind is my favorite.

14:49.520 --> 14:54.520
Oh, I have got a name for this nice baby.

14:54.520 --> 14:57.520
It is sporty.

15:01.520 --> 15:11.520
Chapter five.

15:11.520 --> 15:16.520
A trick.

15:16.520 --> 15:20.520
Sporty is walking with his mum.

15:20.520 --> 15:25.520
He is one or two weeks because they are not walking with other giraffes.

15:25.520 --> 15:28.520
He is too young for that.

15:28.520 --> 15:30.520
I look at Bill.

15:30.520 --> 15:32.520
Oh no.

15:32.520 --> 15:37.520
He is looking at my spotty and smiling.

15:37.520 --> 15:40.520
He likes him too.

15:40.520 --> 15:46.520
Now he starts walking to the mum and her baby.

15:46.520 --> 15:50.520
I hope giraffes are clever animals.

15:50.520 --> 15:56.520
This small walking thing, Bill, doesn't look like a tree.

15:56.520 --> 16:01.520
Tree is a tall and smell nice.

16:01.520 --> 16:04.520
But Bill isn't so silly.

16:04.520 --> 16:12.520
He stops and breaks off some small twigs with juicy green leaves.

16:12.520 --> 16:17.520
Oh, he is holding a lot of twigs.

16:17.520 --> 16:22.520
Now he smells nice for giraffes.

16:22.520 --> 16:27.520
He walks on and I walk behind him.

16:27.520 --> 16:32.520
I think and think how I can stop him.

16:32.520 --> 16:36.520
Suddenly, I have an idea.

16:36.520 --> 16:41.520
You know, I am very good at making animal sounds.

16:41.520 --> 16:48.520
I put my hands to my mouth and make a terrible lion roar.

16:48.520 --> 16:54.520
Bill jumps up, drops his twigs and turns around fast.

16:54.520 --> 16:59.520
I look afraid too.

16:59.520 --> 17:02.520
There is a lion here, he cries.

17:02.520 --> 17:04.520
He is shaking.

17:04.520 --> 17:06.520
His face is white.

17:06.520 --> 17:08.520
He looks at a tall tree.

17:08.520 --> 17:12.520
Jack, we must climb a tree, he says.

17:12.520 --> 17:17.520
That tree hasn't got low branches, so I can't understand how we can climb it.

17:17.520 --> 17:19.520
But Bill can.

17:19.520 --> 17:23.520
He is on top of the tree in a second.

17:23.520 --> 17:25.520
Wow.

17:25.520 --> 17:29.520
He is very strong.

17:29.520 --> 17:34.520
Now, Bill is sitting in the tree and looking around.

17:34.520 --> 17:38.520
Jack, come here, he cries.

17:38.520 --> 17:41.520
But I don't want to climb a tree.

17:41.520 --> 17:44.520
It is too hot.

17:44.520 --> 17:46.520
Are there any lions?

17:46.520 --> 17:48.520
I ask.

17:48.520 --> 17:52.520
I can't see any, he cries.

17:52.520 --> 17:58.520
But Bill is too afraid to climb down.

17:58.520 --> 18:00.520
I am looking at him.

18:00.520 --> 18:05.520
He looks like a thick branch with five green leaves.

18:05.520 --> 18:11.520
It is interesting how long he can sit in a tree.

18:11.520 --> 18:14.520
I sit down on the grass.

18:14.520 --> 18:16.520
It is very hot.

18:16.520 --> 18:19.520
But I am under a tree.

18:19.520 --> 18:21.520
It is great here.

18:21.520 --> 18:26.520
Now, I can have a rest.

18:26.520 --> 18:37.520
Chapter 6.

18:37.520 --> 18:41.520
A bath.

18:41.520 --> 18:47.520
Spotty and his mum are going to Bill's tree.

18:47.520 --> 18:51.520
They are next to it now.

18:51.520 --> 18:55.520
The mother starts eating leaves on the tree.

18:55.520 --> 18:58.520
I can see her tongue.

18:58.520 --> 19:01.520
It is so long.

19:01.520 --> 19:07.520
It is half a metre long.

19:07.520 --> 19:11.520
Then I look at Bill.

19:11.520 --> 19:13.520
He is shaking.

19:13.520 --> 19:15.520
Oh no!

19:15.520 --> 19:18.520
He is afraid of Spotty's mum.

19:18.520 --> 19:22.520
Or is he afraid of her big tongue?

19:22.520 --> 19:25.520
Bill hides in the leaves.

19:25.520 --> 19:29.520
But Spotty's mum eats very fast.

19:29.520 --> 19:33.520
Soon there are no leaves on the tree.

19:33.520 --> 19:36.520
And Bill can't hide in them.

19:36.520 --> 19:37.520
He looks down.

19:37.520 --> 19:39.520
He wants to jump.

19:39.520 --> 19:41.520
Never.

19:41.520 --> 19:44.520
I open my mouth and make a terrible...

19:44.520 --> 19:49.520
Again.

19:49.520 --> 19:53.520
Bill's head is in his shoulders now.

19:53.520 --> 19:57.520
He doesn't want to jump down anymore.

19:57.520 --> 20:00.520
The mother's tongue is next to Bill.

20:00.520 --> 20:05.520
First, it licks his head.

20:05.520 --> 20:09.520
Then it licks his face and ears.

20:09.520 --> 20:13.520
I think Bill is very clean now.

20:13.520 --> 20:18.520
Then Spotty's mum puts her tongue away and looks at Bill.

20:18.520 --> 20:21.520
He is wet.

20:21.520 --> 20:24.520
And he's afraid too.

20:24.520 --> 20:27.520
Suddenly he smiles at the mother.

20:27.520 --> 20:30.520
She looks very surprised.

20:30.520 --> 20:35.520
It is the first time a tree smiles at her.

20:35.520 --> 20:37.520
She gets angry.

20:37.520 --> 20:38.520
Oh no!

20:38.520 --> 20:43.520
She starts shaking the tree with her horns and neck.

20:43.520 --> 20:46.520
Poor Bill.

20:46.520 --> 20:52.520
He is holding by the branches, but the mother is very strong.

20:52.520 --> 20:55.520
Now I am afraid too.

20:55.520 --> 21:00.520
If Bill falls down, he can break his neck.

21:00.520 --> 21:06.520
Suddenly, Spotty puts his nose to his mum.

21:06.520 --> 21:07.520
He is thirsty.

21:07.520 --> 21:09.520
He wants his milk.

21:09.520 --> 21:15.520
So she stops shaking the tree and licks Spotty.

21:15.520 --> 21:20.520
Bill climbs down the tree very fast and runs to me.

21:20.520 --> 21:24.520
He hides behind my tree.

21:24.520 --> 21:29.520
He looks ugly, but happy.

21:29.520 --> 21:31.520
Oh Jack!

21:31.520 --> 21:37.520
This mother giraffe is terrible, he cries.

21:37.520 --> 21:42.520
I think he is terrible, but I don't say it to him.

21:42.520 --> 21:45.520
I am looking at my giraffes.

21:45.520 --> 21:47.520
They are eating.

21:47.520 --> 21:51.520
The mother is four meters tall.

21:51.520 --> 21:55.520
She needs a lot of leaves to be so big.

21:55.520 --> 21:59.520
And Spotty needs a lot of milk to be like his mum.

21:59.520 --> 22:04.520
Eat, dear Spotty, eat and grow fast.

22:04.520 --> 22:07.520
Then no silly Bill can catch you.

22:13.520 --> 22:20.520
Chapter 7

22:20.520 --> 22:25.520
Do you like insects?

22:25.520 --> 22:28.520
I am watching Spotty.

22:28.520 --> 22:30.520
He is so cute.

22:30.520 --> 22:33.520
He isn't drinking milk anymore.

22:33.520 --> 22:35.520
He is jumping.

22:35.520 --> 22:38.520
He wants to play.

22:39.520 --> 22:42.520
Now I can see a shadow.

22:42.520 --> 22:49.520
It is the shadow of a rope with a loop.

22:49.520 --> 22:57.520
Bill is holding it and coming to the giraffes.

22:57.520 --> 23:01.520
He is hiding behind every bush.

23:01.520 --> 23:06.520
He is very slow.

23:07.520 --> 23:12.520
Suddenly Spotty's mum starts running.

23:12.520 --> 23:15.520
Spotty runs with her.

23:15.520 --> 23:21.520
Soon they are far from Bill and me.

23:21.520 --> 23:23.520
I look at Bill.

23:23.520 --> 23:26.520
He isn't hiding anymore.

23:26.520 --> 23:28.520
He is angry.

23:28.520 --> 23:31.520
He can't catch them again.

23:31.520 --> 23:35.520
I climb a tree and look around.

23:35.520 --> 23:37.520
I can see my giraffes.

23:37.520 --> 23:39.520
They are running and playing.

23:39.520 --> 23:43.520
They look so funny now.

23:43.520 --> 23:47.520
But they are running in a circle.

23:47.520 --> 23:49.520
Soon they are coming back.

23:49.520 --> 23:51.520
They are close again.

23:51.520 --> 23:55.520
Look, Bill says.

23:55.520 --> 23:59.520
There are small birds on the mother and her baby.

23:59.520 --> 24:02.520
Do birds live on giraffes?

24:02.520 --> 24:05.520
Of course they don't, I say.

24:05.520 --> 24:07.520
They eat on giraffes.

24:07.520 --> 24:10.520
Giraffes are their dining room.

24:10.520 --> 24:12.520
How terrible!

24:12.520 --> 24:14.520
Bill cries.

24:14.520 --> 24:18.520
I don't want to be somebody's dining room.

24:18.520 --> 24:21.520
Have you got insects in your hair?

24:21.520 --> 24:24.520
I ask.

24:24.520 --> 24:26.520
Insects in my hair?

24:26.520 --> 24:31.520
Bill looks afraid and puts his fingers in his hair.

24:31.520 --> 24:34.520
Those birds eat insects.

24:34.520 --> 24:38.520
They are their favorite food, I say.

24:38.520 --> 24:41.520
Are there insects on giraffes?

24:41.520 --> 24:43.520
Bill asks.

24:43.520 --> 24:45.520
He looks surprised.

24:45.520 --> 24:48.520
Yes, there are a lot of them.

24:48.520 --> 24:52.520
When you catch the baby and take it home,

24:52.520 --> 24:56.520
you can have a lot of insects too.

24:56.520 --> 25:00.520
So it's a good idea to take three birds with you.

25:00.520 --> 25:04.520
One for the baby and two for Jill and you.

25:04.520 --> 25:08.520
But Jill doesn't like birds, Bill says.

25:08.520 --> 25:11.520
Then I hope she likes insects, I say.

25:11.520 --> 25:13.520
No, Bill cries.

25:13.520 --> 25:15.520
She doesn't.

25:15.520 --> 25:20.520
If Jill likes the giraffe, she must like its insects.

25:20.520 --> 25:25.520
There are no giraffes without insects on them.

25:25.520 --> 25:28.520
Bill starts thinking.

25:28.520 --> 25:34.520
Look, Jack, I can wash our giraffe in the bathroom.

25:34.520 --> 25:37.520
In Jill's bathroom, I laugh.

25:37.520 --> 25:40.520
Are you crazy?

25:40.520 --> 25:43.520
Bill looks at me and thinks again.

25:43.520 --> 25:49.520
Then I can wash it in the garden or take it to the lake.

25:49.520 --> 25:54.520
You can have a lot of problems with that baby, I say.

25:54.520 --> 25:58.520
I'm looking at him and he is looking at me.

25:58.520 --> 26:00.520
Poor Bill.

26:00.520 --> 26:02.520
He loves my sister.

26:02.520 --> 26:05.520
He's ready to do everything for her.

26:05.520 --> 26:08.520
Birds can't change it.

26:08.520 --> 26:11.520
Even terrible insects can't change it.

26:11.520 --> 26:25.520
Chapter 8.

26:25.520 --> 26:29.520
A strange animal.

26:29.520 --> 26:33.520
Now, Bill does a strange thing.

26:33.520 --> 26:42.520
He ties a long branch to the back of his neck and head.

26:42.520 --> 26:47.520
Then he puts his hands on the grass.

26:47.520 --> 26:52.520
Now he has got four legs and a long neck.

26:52.520 --> 26:59.520
But there's no head on that neck, only some twigs.

26:59.520 --> 27:03.520
I think Spotty's mum is very clever.

27:03.520 --> 27:09.520
She can't make friends with a giraffe with twigs instead of a head.

27:09.520 --> 27:13.520
But Bill can't understand that.

27:13.520 --> 27:22.520
He hasn't got a head now and he can't think.

27:22.520 --> 27:26.520
Spotty and mother are walking.

27:26.520 --> 27:31.520
Suddenly, they see two big giraffes.

27:31.520 --> 27:34.520
They are very tall.

27:34.520 --> 27:41.520
They're standing together and hitting each other with their necks.

27:41.520 --> 27:43.520
What are they doing?

27:43.520 --> 27:46.520
Ask Spotty.

27:46.520 --> 27:50.520
Is it a game?

27:50.520 --> 27:54.520
They're fighting, mother says.

27:54.520 --> 27:56.520
Is it good or bad?

27:56.520 --> 27:59.520
Ask Spotty.

27:59.520 --> 28:04.520
All big giraffes sometimes fight, mother says.

28:04.520 --> 28:07.520
Why?

28:07.520 --> 28:09.520
Stand and look.

28:09.520 --> 28:11.520
And I must eat.

28:11.520 --> 28:14.520
I'm very hungry.

28:14.520 --> 28:18.520
So mother starts eating acacia leaves.

28:18.520 --> 28:21.520
They are giraffes' favorite food.

28:21.520 --> 28:25.520
And Spotty is looking at the big giraffes.

28:25.520 --> 28:29.520
They fight and fight.

28:29.520 --> 28:31.520
Now they're very tired.

28:31.520 --> 28:36.520
Suddenly, one giraffe turns and walks away.

28:36.520 --> 28:38.520
He looks sad.

28:38.520 --> 28:41.520
The other giraffe looks very proud.

28:41.520 --> 28:45.520
He goes to a beautiful lady giraffe.

28:45.520 --> 28:48.520
Look at me, he says.

28:48.520 --> 28:50.520
I'm so strong.

28:50.520 --> 28:52.520
My neck is so long.

28:52.520 --> 28:56.520
My spots are so dark.

28:56.520 --> 28:58.520
I'm a cool boy.

28:58.520 --> 29:01.520
And you're a cool girl.

29:01.520 --> 29:05.520
Let's be together.

29:05.520 --> 29:08.520
But the lady giraffe doesn't look at him.

29:08.520 --> 29:11.520
She eats and eats.

29:11.520 --> 29:16.520
So the big giraffe gets very sad and goes away.

29:16.520 --> 29:22.520
Mom, that lady giraffe is silly, Spotty says.

29:22.520 --> 29:26.520
When I grow up, I don't want to fight for girls.

29:26.520 --> 29:28.520
I have my lady giraffe.

29:28.520 --> 29:30.520
It's you.

29:30.520 --> 29:35.520
And he licks mother.

29:35.520 --> 29:37.520
Let's wait and see.

29:37.520 --> 29:40.520
Mother smiles.

29:40.520 --> 29:44.520
Suddenly, she stops smiling.

29:44.520 --> 29:47.520
She's looking at something.

29:47.520 --> 29:50.520
Spotty looks at it too.

29:50.520 --> 29:54.520
There is a strange animal there.

29:54.520 --> 29:56.520
What's that?

29:56.520 --> 29:59.520
Asks Spotty.

29:59.520 --> 30:01.520
I don't know, mother answers.

30:01.520 --> 30:03.520
It's a very strange animal.

30:03.520 --> 30:06.520
Trees grow out of its neck.

30:06.520 --> 30:09.520
I'm afraid, cries Spotty.

30:09.520 --> 30:11.520
You're right.

30:11.520 --> 30:13.520
Never come up to strange animals.

30:13.520 --> 30:17.520
Even if your favorite food grows out of them.

30:17.520 --> 30:20.520
Let's run away, says Spotty.

30:20.520 --> 30:25.520
Spotty and mother run very fast.

30:25.520 --> 30:32.520
Bill is standing on his hands and feet and looking at them.

30:32.520 --> 30:37.520
They don't like me, he says to me.

30:37.520 --> 30:39.520
I understand them.

30:39.520 --> 30:45.520
But I don't say it to Bill.

30:53.520 --> 30:55.520
Chapter 9.

30:55.520 --> 30:58.520
A waterhole.

30:58.520 --> 31:01.520
Spotty's mum is thirsty.

31:01.520 --> 31:05.520
I know that because she's going to a waterhole.

31:05.520 --> 31:08.520
The waterhole is big.

31:08.520 --> 31:11.520
But there's a lot of mud around it.

31:11.520 --> 31:14.520
It's very bad for giraffes.

31:14.520 --> 31:19.520
They can fall in the mud and often can't get up.

31:19.520 --> 31:22.520
Then they die there.

31:22.520 --> 31:26.520
So I'm very afraid for Spotty and his mum.

31:26.520 --> 31:29.520
But Bill is happy.

31:29.520 --> 31:32.520
Great, he cries.

31:32.520 --> 31:34.520
When they're in the mud,

31:34.520 --> 31:37.520
we can catch the baby.

31:37.520 --> 31:43.520
Again he ticks the rope in his hands and goes to the waterhole.

31:43.520 --> 31:46.520
I can't stop Spotty's mum.

31:46.520 --> 31:48.520
She's in the mud now.

31:48.520 --> 31:54.520
But she says something to Spotty because he doesn't go after her.

31:54.520 --> 31:57.520
He walks around the mud.

31:57.520 --> 32:00.520
Now the mother stops.

32:00.520 --> 32:03.520
She puts her legs far from each other.

32:03.520 --> 32:07.520
Then she puts her neck down.

32:07.520 --> 32:10.520
Now her mouth can get the water.

32:10.520 --> 32:15.520
She looks very funny when she's drinking like that.

32:19.520 --> 32:22.520
It's time to catch the baby.

32:22.520 --> 32:25.520
Bill says his mum can't help him.

32:25.520 --> 32:29.520
I don't know what to do, but I must do something.

32:29.520 --> 32:33.520
So I say, who knows?

32:33.520 --> 32:36.520
She's strong and runs fast.

32:36.520 --> 32:39.520
Let's catch her first.

32:39.520 --> 32:44.520
Bill looks at the mother and then at a big tree next to the mud.

32:44.520 --> 32:46.520
You're right.

32:46.520 --> 32:49.520
We should tie her to that tree, he says.

32:49.520 --> 32:54.520
Bill gets the rope and we come up to the mud.

32:54.520 --> 32:58.520
Bill wants to throw the loop around the mother's neck.

32:58.520 --> 33:02.520
But I say, the rope is too short.

33:02.520 --> 33:06.520
You must stand in the mud.

33:06.520 --> 33:10.520
Bill looks at the rope and then at Spotty's mum.

33:10.520 --> 33:14.520
He walks into the mud.

33:14.520 --> 33:17.520
Now you stay here, I say.

33:17.520 --> 33:20.520
I must run round and stand opposite her.

33:20.520 --> 33:24.520
Remember, I'm the red light.

33:24.520 --> 33:27.520
Oh, I see, Bill says.

33:27.520 --> 33:32.520
Jack, you are cool.

33:32.520 --> 33:36.520
So I run around the waterhole and stand opposite Spotty's mum.

33:36.520 --> 33:39.520
I hope she can see me.

33:39.520 --> 33:41.520
Yes, she can.

33:41.520 --> 33:44.520
She stops drinking and looks at me.

33:44.520 --> 33:47.520
She can see my red colour.

33:47.520 --> 33:49.520
She doesn't like it.

33:49.520 --> 33:53.520
She turns her neck to look at Spotty.

33:53.520 --> 33:58.520
At this moment, Bill throws the rope.

34:12.520 --> 34:14.520
Chapter 10.

34:14.520 --> 34:18.520
In the mud.

34:18.520 --> 34:21.520
Oh no.

34:21.520 --> 34:24.520
The loop is around the mother's neck.

34:24.520 --> 34:27.520
But she is very strong.

34:27.520 --> 34:30.520
She doesn't fall.

34:30.520 --> 34:34.520
She starts turning her neck left and right.

34:34.520 --> 34:38.520
Bill is holding the rope.

34:38.520 --> 34:40.520
But he can't stand anymore.

34:40.520 --> 34:42.520
He falls into the mud.

34:42.520 --> 34:47.520
The mother starts turning her body.

34:47.520 --> 34:50.520
Help me, Jack.

34:51.520 --> 34:54.520
I can't swim, cries Bill.

34:54.520 --> 34:57.520
Don't be sad, I cry.

34:57.520 --> 34:59.520
Nobody can swim in the mud.

34:59.520 --> 35:01.520
It's normal.

35:01.520 --> 35:03.520
But Bill is sad.

35:03.520 --> 35:05.520
He's sitting in the mud.

35:05.520 --> 35:08.520
He's dirty.

35:08.520 --> 35:12.520
I'm very dirty, he cries.

35:12.520 --> 35:15.520
Don't be sad, I repeat.

35:15.520 --> 35:17.520
You can't be clean in the mud.

35:17.520 --> 35:19.520
You must be dirty.

35:19.520 --> 35:21.520
It's normal.

35:21.520 --> 35:26.520
At that moment, Spotty's mum stops turning her neck.

35:26.520 --> 35:30.520
She starts walking to Bill.

35:30.520 --> 35:32.520
Bill, I cry.

35:32.520 --> 35:35.520
The mother is going to you.

35:35.520 --> 35:38.520
I don't think she wants to make friends with you.

35:38.520 --> 35:42.520
Drop the rope and get out.

35:42.520 --> 35:46.520
Bill looks at Spotty's mum.

35:46.520 --> 35:48.520
He is afraid.

35:48.520 --> 35:51.520
He drops the rope and wants to run.

35:51.520 --> 35:54.520
But he can't.

35:54.520 --> 35:57.520
Now I am afraid for Bill.

35:57.520 --> 36:00.520
Go under the mud, I cry.

36:00.520 --> 36:03.520
Bill does so.

36:03.520 --> 36:06.520
Now the mother can't see him.

36:06.520 --> 36:08.520
She walks out of the mud.

36:08.520 --> 36:13.520
Spotty runs to her.

36:13.520 --> 36:16.520
Then go to an acacia.

36:16.520 --> 36:20.520
The mother puts her long neck in the tree.

36:20.520 --> 36:24.520
She turns her head left and right.

36:24.520 --> 36:31.520
The acacia has got a lot of thorns, but they never hurt giraffes.

36:31.520 --> 36:34.520
Now the loop is around many thorns.

36:34.520 --> 36:38.520
It gets big, and then very big.

36:38.520 --> 36:42.520
Soon, Spotty's mum takes her head out of it.

36:42.520 --> 36:45.520
She's free.

36:45.520 --> 36:49.520
Hooray, I cry.

36:49.520 --> 36:53.520
At that moment I can see Bill's head above the mud.

36:53.520 --> 36:54.520
He's looking at me.

36:54.520 --> 36:56.520
Hooray, hooray, I repeat.

36:56.520 --> 36:57.520
You're here.

36:57.520 --> 36:59.520
You're okay.

36:59.520 --> 37:02.520
I'm not okay, save Bill.

37:02.520 --> 37:05.520
I haven't got my shorts anymore.

37:05.520 --> 37:07.520
They're there.

37:07.520 --> 37:10.520
And he looks down at the mud.

37:15.520 --> 37:19.520
Oh, mummy, you are free, Christ Spotty.

37:19.520 --> 37:21.520
He's very happy.

37:21.520 --> 37:23.520
Yes, I am.

37:23.520 --> 37:25.520
Let's run away from here.

37:25.520 --> 37:28.520
It's that strange animal again.

37:28.520 --> 37:31.520
They start running.

37:31.520 --> 37:36.520
Is it a crocodile, ask Spotty?

37:36.520 --> 37:41.520
It can be because it goes under the mud, says mother.

37:41.520 --> 37:46.520
But crocodiles haven't got long, thin tongues.

37:46.520 --> 37:50.520
And they don't catch animals with their tongues.

37:50.520 --> 37:53.520
I know, I know, Christ Spotty.

37:53.520 --> 37:56.520
This is a very old crocodile.

37:56.520 --> 37:59.520
It's got no teeth.

37:59.520 --> 38:03.520
That's why it catches animals with its tongue.

38:03.520 --> 38:08.520
I think you are right, my clever boy, Smiles' mother.

38:12.520 --> 38:21.520
Chapter 11.

38:21.520 --> 38:24.520
Fishing for shorts.

38:28.520 --> 38:31.520
Bill and I are in the mud.

38:31.520 --> 38:35.520
We're looking for Bill's shorts.

38:35.520 --> 38:38.520
There are some interesting things in the mud.

38:38.520 --> 38:44.520
There's a ball, a shoe, and two socks.

38:44.520 --> 38:47.520
Why are they here?

38:47.520 --> 38:53.520
I think Bill isn't the first man who gets into this mud.

38:53.520 --> 38:56.520
A nice collection, I say.

38:56.520 --> 39:01.520
You can take these socks instead of your shorts.

39:01.520 --> 39:06.520
But I don't need socks, Christ Bill.

39:06.520 --> 39:08.520
Why, I ask.

39:08.520 --> 39:12.520
Look, I think they're green when they are clean.

39:12.520 --> 39:15.520
They match your gloves.

39:15.520 --> 39:19.520
Stop it, Jack, says Bill.

39:19.520 --> 39:22.520
He's angry now.

39:22.520 --> 39:25.520
If you like these socks, you can take them.

39:25.520 --> 39:29.520
I need my shorts.

39:29.520 --> 39:33.520
Bill is very sad.

39:33.520 --> 39:36.520
But I am very happy.

39:36.520 --> 39:39.520
We're not going after the giraffes.

39:39.520 --> 39:41.520
We're staying here.

39:41.520 --> 39:44.520
We must find his shorts.

39:44.520 --> 39:47.520
I look at Spotty and his mum.

39:47.520 --> 39:49.520
They aren't very far.

39:49.520 --> 39:52.520
They're eating again.

39:52.520 --> 39:55.520
Look, Jack, Bill says.

39:55.520 --> 39:58.520
Those terrible animals are eating.

39:58.520 --> 40:01.520
Eating again, and I'm hungry like a wolf.

40:01.520 --> 40:07.520
I'm dirty, too, and I haven't got my shorts.

40:07.520 --> 40:11.520
Suddenly, I can feel something in the mud.

40:11.520 --> 40:13.520
I take it out.

40:13.520 --> 40:16.520
They are Bill's shorts.

40:16.520 --> 40:19.520
Bill isn't looking at me.

40:19.520 --> 40:24.520
So I put them back in the mud and sit down on them.

40:24.520 --> 40:26.520
Can you feel anything?

40:26.520 --> 40:29.520
Asks Bill.

40:29.520 --> 40:32.520
He's on his hands and knees in the mud.

40:32.520 --> 40:34.520
No, I answer.

40:34.520 --> 40:37.520
Nothing.

40:37.520 --> 40:41.520
Why are you sitting and doing nothing?

40:41.520 --> 40:42.520
Bill is angry again.

40:42.520 --> 40:46.520
Help me.

40:46.520 --> 40:49.520
I stand on my hands and knees.

40:49.520 --> 40:52.520
Bill is next to me now.

40:52.520 --> 40:54.520
I look at my giraffes again.

40:54.520 --> 40:58.520
Ray, now they are far away.

40:58.520 --> 41:02.520
And they're close to other giraffes with their babies.

41:02.520 --> 41:06.520
They all look like Spotty and his mum.

41:06.520 --> 41:10.520
Bill can't catch Spotty now.

41:10.520 --> 41:14.520
He must be afraid of so many giraffes together.

41:14.520 --> 41:17.520
I take his shorts out of the mud.

41:17.520 --> 41:19.520
Look, Bill.

41:19.520 --> 41:23.520
Are they yours, I ask?

41:23.520 --> 41:28.520
Bill is very happy.

41:28.520 --> 41:29.520
Thank you, Jack.

41:29.520 --> 41:32.520
You're a good friend, he smiles.

41:32.520 --> 41:37.520
Bill tries to put on his shorts.

41:37.520 --> 41:43.520
But they are too wet and dirty.

41:43.520 --> 41:48.520
What can I do, he asks.

41:48.520 --> 41:54.520
I think we should go home and wash our clothes, I say.

41:54.520 --> 42:02.520
At that moment, we can hear a terrible noise from the sky.

42:02.520 --> 42:04.520
We look up.

42:04.520 --> 42:07.520
The sky is very black.

42:07.520 --> 42:11.520
Then it starts raining.

42:11.520 --> 42:14.520
Yes, cries Bill.

42:14.520 --> 42:20.520
He is very happy, but I am very sad.

42:20.520 --> 42:25.520
No, I say.

42:25.520 --> 42:30.520
Bill can't hear me because the rain is too noisy.

42:30.520 --> 42:42.520
Chapter 12.

42:42.520 --> 42:49.520
Too many babies.

42:49.520 --> 42:57.520
When the rain stops, we are wet, but clean.

42:57.520 --> 43:00.520
Bill is very happy.

43:00.520 --> 43:03.520
He starts singing.

43:03.520 --> 43:05.520
Where are you, giraffes?

43:05.520 --> 43:15.520
I have got green gloves on my strong big hands to catch you, my friends.

43:15.520 --> 43:19.520
You've got too many friends, I say.

43:19.520 --> 43:22.520
Look there.

43:22.520 --> 43:26.520
Bill looks and sees eight or ten giraffes.

43:26.520 --> 43:29.520
Some of them are babies.

43:29.520 --> 43:32.520
Some big giraffes are sleeping.

43:32.520 --> 43:36.520
Their heads are next to their tails.

43:36.520 --> 43:40.520
My dog sleeps like that.

43:40.520 --> 43:43.520
Look, cries Bill.

43:43.520 --> 43:46.520
All the big giraffes are sleeping.

43:46.520 --> 43:50.520
We can catch the baby.

43:50.520 --> 43:52.520
Not all, I say.

43:52.520 --> 43:55.520
The big giraffe on the left isn't sleeping.

43:55.520 --> 43:58.520
It is on guard.

43:58.520 --> 44:01.520
There can't be, Bill says.

44:01.520 --> 44:05.520
Giraffes are silly animals.

44:05.520 --> 44:07.520
Okay, I say.

44:07.520 --> 44:11.520
Then try to catch Spotty.

44:11.520 --> 44:16.520
Who is Spotty asks Bill?

44:16.520 --> 44:19.520
Our baby giraffe, I answer.

44:19.520 --> 44:23.520
Only which is Spotty.

44:23.520 --> 44:26.520
The one next to the bushes says Bill.

44:26.520 --> 44:29.520
No, the one behind that tall tree.

44:29.520 --> 44:32.520
There are five baby giraffes.

44:32.520 --> 44:34.520
Bill looks and looks.

44:34.520 --> 44:39.520
Let's catch the one between the trees and the bushes, I say.

44:39.520 --> 44:42.520
Bill takes the rope and goes to the baby.

44:42.520 --> 44:43.520
The baby can see us.

44:43.520 --> 44:48.520
It turns and runs to the guard giraffe.

44:48.520 --> 44:51.520
That's bad, says Bill.

44:51.520 --> 44:53.520
We must catch another one.

44:53.520 --> 45:00.520
He goes to the bushes, but another baby looks at Bill and runs to the guard giraffe too.

45:00.520 --> 45:02.520
They are clever.

45:02.520 --> 45:05.520
These silly giraffes, says Bill.

45:05.520 --> 45:08.520
He's angry.

45:08.520 --> 45:12.520
Let's tie the big giraffe to a tree, I say.

45:12.520 --> 45:15.520
Then we can catch a small one.

45:15.520 --> 45:19.520
No, cries Bill, not again.

45:19.520 --> 45:22.520
He looks at me.

45:22.520 --> 45:26.520
I don't like his eyes.

45:26.520 --> 45:31.520
At that moment, he sees a third baby.

45:31.520 --> 45:36.520
It is opposite a bush with big pink flowers.

45:36.520 --> 45:39.520
The baby can't see Bill.

45:39.520 --> 45:43.520
It is smelling the flowers.

45:43.520 --> 45:50.520
Aha, cries Bill and runs to the baby.

45:50.520 --> 45:54.520
I don't know what to do.

45:54.520 --> 46:12.520
Again, I put my hands around my mouth and roar.

46:12.520 --> 46:15.520
That is thirteen.

46:15.520 --> 46:20.520
What are they doing?

46:20.520 --> 46:23.520
It is a terrible roar.

46:23.520 --> 46:28.520
But this time, Bill turns too fast.

46:28.520 --> 46:32.520
You can see my face and hands around my mouth.

46:32.520 --> 46:34.520
What are you doing?

46:34.520 --> 46:36.520
He cries.

46:36.520 --> 46:41.520
I'm sneezing, I say, and roar again.

46:41.520 --> 46:47.520
Again, sneezing, I'm sorry, I always sneeze like that.

46:47.520 --> 46:52.520
Bill's face is very strange now.

46:52.520 --> 46:57.520
He puts his hands in front of him and makes fists.

46:57.520 --> 47:02.520
At that moment, we can hear a terrible noise.

47:02.520 --> 47:07.520
I look behind Bill.

47:07.520 --> 47:13.520
All the big giraffes and their babies are running at us.

47:13.520 --> 47:15.520
Look out, Bill.

47:15.520 --> 47:17.520
I cry.

47:17.520 --> 47:22.520
Bill looks round and sees the giraffes and jumps up.

47:22.520 --> 47:24.520
Then he starts running.

47:24.520 --> 47:26.520
I run too.

47:26.520 --> 47:28.520
We run and run.

47:28.520 --> 47:34.520
There is that muddy waterhole in front of us.

47:34.520 --> 47:36.520
Jump.

47:36.520 --> 47:41.520
Bill and I cry together.

47:41.520 --> 47:46.520
We are with our heads in the mud again.

47:46.520 --> 47:52.520
When we're out of the mud, we can't see any giraffes.

47:52.520 --> 47:57.520
There are no giraffes next to the trees or bushes.

47:57.520 --> 48:02.520
There are no giraffes on the grass.

48:02.520 --> 48:06.520
But there are other animals.

48:06.520 --> 48:12.520
These animals have got very big ears.

48:12.520 --> 48:16.520
And they are very angry.

48:16.520 --> 48:22.520
They are hitting trees and the trees are falling onto the ground.

48:22.520 --> 48:27.520
They are elephants.

48:27.520 --> 48:30.520
What are they doing asks Bill?

48:30.520 --> 48:33.520
He's afraid.

48:33.520 --> 48:37.520
They're breaking trees, I answer.

48:37.520 --> 48:40.520
I can see that, Bill says.

48:40.520 --> 48:46.520
Why are they doing it?

48:46.520 --> 48:51.520
I'm thinking what to say.

48:51.520 --> 48:56.520
Suddenly, I've got an idea.

48:56.520 --> 49:00.520
They're playing hide and seek with the giraffes.

49:00.520 --> 49:02.520
Look.

49:02.520 --> 49:05.520
There are no giraffes.

49:05.520 --> 49:08.520
They're hiding from the elephants.

49:08.520 --> 49:10.520
Bill is surprised.

49:10.520 --> 49:13.520
How do you know, he asks.

49:13.520 --> 49:16.520
My dad knows a lot about different animals.

49:16.520 --> 49:19.520
Elephants and giraffes are good friends.

49:19.520 --> 49:21.520
They often play together.

49:21.520 --> 49:24.520
Elephants are very clever.

49:24.520 --> 49:29.520
If they break down all the trees and bushes, giraffes can't hide behind them.

49:29.520 --> 49:32.520
Then elephants find them.

49:32.520 --> 49:38.520
And what do they do after that asks Bill?

49:38.520 --> 49:42.520
Then elephants hide from giraffes.

49:42.520 --> 49:46.520
Only giraffes are very tall and can see very far.

49:46.520 --> 49:49.520
And elephants are too fat.

49:49.520 --> 49:53.520
So giraffes can see elephants behind trees and bushes.

49:53.520 --> 49:58.520
Where do elephants hide then asks Bill?

49:58.520 --> 50:06.520
They jump into a waterhole and hide in the mud, I answer.

50:06.520 --> 50:16.520
This waterhole, Bill's eyes get very big and his face changes its color.

50:16.520 --> 50:18.520
Any waterhole.

50:18.520 --> 50:22.520
Only I can't see another one here, I say.

50:22.520 --> 50:26.520
Bill looks at me, then he cries.

50:26.520 --> 50:30.520
Mummy!

50:30.520 --> 50:32.520
And runs out of the mud.

50:32.520 --> 50:35.520
I run after him.

50:35.520 --> 50:41.520
We run and run, then Bill gets tired and falls on the ground.

50:41.520 --> 50:44.520
I sit down next to him.

50:53.520 --> 50:56.520
Chapter 14.

50:56.520 --> 51:01.520
Heroine.

51:01.520 --> 51:05.520
Where's sitting on the grass?

51:05.520 --> 51:08.520
Can you see any elephant?

51:08.520 --> 51:10.520
Bill asks me.

51:10.520 --> 51:13.520
No, I can't, I say.

51:13.520 --> 51:16.520
Are there any giraffes?

51:16.520 --> 51:18.520
He asks again.

51:18.520 --> 51:20.520
I look around.

51:21.520 --> 51:24.520
Now there are some giraffes close to us.

51:24.520 --> 51:29.520
I can even see spotty and his mum.

51:29.520 --> 51:32.520
Yes, I say.

51:32.520 --> 51:40.520
Suddenly Bill says, we're so dirty.

51:40.520 --> 51:43.520
Let's go home now.

51:43.520 --> 51:48.520
Tomorrow we can take some carrots and apples with us.

51:48.520 --> 51:50.520
A great idea, I say.

51:50.520 --> 51:53.520
We should take some cabbages and watermelons too.

51:53.520 --> 51:58.520
They're giraffes' favorite food.

51:58.520 --> 52:02.520
Are you crazy, Bill cries?

52:02.520 --> 52:04.520
How can we take them?

52:04.520 --> 52:10.520
They're so heavy.

52:10.520 --> 52:12.520
We can roll, then I say.

52:12.520 --> 52:14.520
Bill is looking at me.

52:14.520 --> 52:17.520
I don't like his face.

52:18.520 --> 52:23.520
I think now he understands what I'm doing here.

52:23.520 --> 52:25.520
Jack, he cries.

52:25.520 --> 52:27.520
Why are you here with me?

52:27.520 --> 52:30.520
First you roar like a lioness.

52:30.520 --> 52:33.520
Then you have that silly idea to tie the mother giraffe.

52:33.520 --> 52:38.520
And now he doesn't finish.

52:38.520 --> 52:42.520
Because we can hear a terrible roar.

52:42.520 --> 52:45.520
And this time it is real.

52:45.520 --> 52:48.520
It's the roar of an angry lioness.

52:48.520 --> 52:50.520
We look back.

52:50.520 --> 52:57.520
We can see her.

52:57.520 --> 52:59.520
The lioness looks at us.

52:59.520 --> 53:01.520
Then at the giraffes.

53:01.520 --> 53:03.520
And again at us.

53:03.520 --> 53:06.520
She's thinking which to eat.

53:06.520 --> 53:09.520
Bill's face is white.

53:09.520 --> 53:13.520
I think mine is white too.

53:13.520 --> 53:15.520
We are too afraid.

53:15.520 --> 53:17.520
We start shaking.

53:17.520 --> 53:22.520
Suddenly, Spotty's mom runs at the lioness.

53:22.520 --> 53:27.520
Her son is running between her legs.

53:27.520 --> 53:30.520
When they come up to the angry animal,

53:30.520 --> 53:38.520
the mother puts up her front legs.

53:38.520 --> 53:42.520
The lioness is afraid.

53:42.520 --> 53:45.520
She starts jumping around the giraffes.

53:45.520 --> 53:51.520
But the mother always turns with her front legs to her and tries to kick.

53:51.520 --> 53:53.520
Hooray!

53:53.520 --> 53:56.520
The lioness is too tired now.

53:56.520 --> 53:58.520
She can't fight anymore.

53:58.520 --> 54:01.520
She turns round and runs away.

54:01.520 --> 54:10.520
Spotty is looking at his brave mother.

54:10.520 --> 54:12.520
I look at Bill.

54:12.520 --> 54:14.520
He looks strange.

54:14.520 --> 54:20.520
Suddenly, he gets up and walks to the giraffes.

54:20.520 --> 54:26.520
Does he want to catch them now when they're too tired?

54:26.520 --> 54:32.520
But Bill stops and puts his head and half of his body down.

54:32.520 --> 54:35.520
Oh, I understand.

54:35.520 --> 54:45.520
He is saying, thank you to the brave mother.

54:45.520 --> 54:51.520
Mom, it's that strange animal again, say Spotty.

54:51.520 --> 54:58.520
Yes, but it's smiling at us and it hasn't got a long tongue in its mouth.

54:58.520 --> 55:01.520
And there's no tree in his neck, say Spotty.

55:01.520 --> 55:03.520
Poor animal.

55:03.520 --> 55:07.520
Can't live long without a tongue.

55:07.520 --> 55:16.520
Spotty turns to a bush, takes some leaves with his tongue and gives them to the strange animal.

55:16.520 --> 55:19.520
You can always come here, he says.

55:19.520 --> 55:30.520
And I can give you tasty leaves, eat them and live long.

55:30.520 --> 55:32.520
Look, Jack.

55:32.520 --> 55:36.520
Your Spotty is giving me a present.

55:36.520 --> 55:40.520
Giraffes are so nice.

55:40.520 --> 55:42.520
Bill takes the leaves.

55:42.520 --> 55:44.520
He looks so funny.

55:44.520 --> 55:50.520
I like him now.

55:51.520 --> 55:58.520
Chapter 15.

55:58.520 --> 56:02.520
A happy end.

56:02.520 --> 56:07.520
Bill isn't very clever, but he is kind.

56:07.520 --> 56:11.520
He can't hunt Spotty anymore.

56:11.520 --> 56:13.520
He looks at me.

56:13.520 --> 56:16.520
Jack, you're right.

56:17.520 --> 56:20.520
It's wrong to catch giraffes.

56:20.520 --> 56:22.520
They must walk free.

56:22.520 --> 56:25.520
But what should I tell Jill?

56:25.520 --> 56:30.520
She can get very angry and I love her.

56:30.520 --> 56:32.520
He sits down on the grass.

56:32.520 --> 56:34.520
He's very sad.

56:34.520 --> 56:37.520
I know what we should do, I say.

56:37.520 --> 56:40.520
Then I talk and talk.

56:40.520 --> 56:43.520
Soon Bill knows my idea.

56:43.520 --> 56:45.520
He likes it.

56:46.520 --> 56:49.520
I hope it helps, he says.

56:49.520 --> 56:52.520
So we take the rope and go home.

56:52.520 --> 56:56.520
The mud on us is dry now, and our skin hurts.

56:56.520 --> 56:59.520
So we can't walk fast.

56:59.520 --> 57:05.520
When we're in front of the door, Jill opens it and jumps up.

57:05.520 --> 57:10.520
What's the matter with you, she cries, and then we say,

57:10.520 --> 57:15.520
Dear Jill, there are lots of giraffes in the grasslands.

57:15.520 --> 57:19.520
They're all very tall and beautiful.

57:19.520 --> 57:22.520
We can't choose only one.

57:22.520 --> 57:27.520
If you want to pet giraffe, let's go to the grasslands together.

57:27.520 --> 57:31.520
Then you can show us your favorite one.

57:31.520 --> 57:37.520
Only don't put on many clothes, put on a swimming costume.

57:37.520 --> 57:40.520
Jill doesn't understand.

57:40.520 --> 57:43.520
A swimming costume.

57:43.520 --> 57:48.520
Why do I need a swimming costume there?

57:48.520 --> 57:52.520
Because there are angry lionesses there, I say.

57:52.520 --> 57:55.520
When they're hungry, they run at you.

57:55.520 --> 57:57.520
They run very fast.

57:57.520 --> 58:03.520
You can't run away from them, so you must hide in a muddy waterhole.

58:04.520 --> 58:08.520
And when you get out of the mud, your clothes are dirty.

58:08.520 --> 58:11.520
And very heavy, says Bill.

58:11.520 --> 58:13.520
Yes, I say.

58:13.520 --> 58:16.520
Then you can't walk fast in them.

58:16.520 --> 58:20.520
And when angry elephants come and start breaking trees,

58:20.520 --> 58:23.520
oh, Jill stops me.

58:23.520 --> 58:26.520
She looks afraid now.

58:26.520 --> 58:30.520
I think I don't need a pet giraffe.

58:30.520 --> 58:32.520
I've got no free time.

58:32.520 --> 58:37.520
And our house isn't very tall.

58:37.520 --> 58:40.520
We can make a big hole in the roof, I say.

58:40.520 --> 58:42.520
Are you crazy?

58:42.520 --> 58:44.520
Jill asks.

58:44.520 --> 58:47.520
I don't want any holes in my roof.

58:47.520 --> 58:48.520
I don't need a giraffe.

58:48.520 --> 58:50.520
That's all.

58:50.520 --> 58:53.520
Okay, we say.

58:53.520 --> 58:56.520
Can we go to the bathroom now?

59:00.520 --> 59:04.520
MUSIC

